{"id":"cond-mat/9807394","submitter":"Karin Dahmen","authors":"Karin A. Dahmen, David R. Nelson, and Nadav M. Shnerb","title":"Life and Death near a Windy Oasis","comments":"18 pages, 9 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn q-bio","license":null,"abstract":"  We propose a simple experiment to study delocalization and extinction in\ninhomogeneous biological systems. The nonlinear steady state for, say, a\nbacteria colony living on and near a patch of nutrient or favorable\nillumination (``oasis'') in the presence of a drift term (``wind'') is\ncomputed. The bacteria, described by a simple generalization of the Fisher\nequation, diffuse, divide A -> A+A, die A -> 0, and annihilate A+A -> 0. At\nhigh wind velocities all bacteria are blown into an unfavorable region\n(``desert''), and the colony dies out. At low velocity a steady state\nconcentration survives near the oasis. In between these two regimes there is a\ncritical velocity at which bacteria first survive. If the ``desert'' supports a\nsmall nonzero population, this extinction transition is replaced by a\ndelocalization transition with increasing velocity. Predictions for the\nbehavior as a function of wind velocity are made for one and two dimensions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 30 Jul 1998 08:02:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
